explanation:
For a precise dead-code (MISRA) analysis we must know the semantics and side-effects of every type/constant and callee used by OS_ObjectIdConvertToken so we can judge whether any executed operation could be removed without changing program behavior. Each listed symbol is required for the reasons below:

- OS_object_token_t: definition of the token structure (fields used here: at least lock_mode and any other fields referenced by called helpers). Needed to know whether reading token->lock_mode or other fields has side-effects or is redundant.

- OS_common_record_t: definition of the object record (fields active_id and refcount). Required to assess whether assignments (obj->active_id = ...) and ++obj->refcount are observable and thus not dead.

- osal_id_t: ID type representation and any associated semantics (size, special values). Needed to decide if comparisons/assignments of IDs have observable effect.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_RESERVED, OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT: lock-mode constants are used in control flow decisions. Their exact numeric values/meanings determine which branches execute and whether some branches can ever be taken (potential dead code if a mode is impossible).

- OS_OBJECT_ID_RESERVED: special reserved ID value. Needed to determine whether overwriting obj->active_id with this value has observable effect and whether comparisons against it can be optimized away.

- OS_SUCCESS, OS_ERROR, OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE, OS_ERR_INVALID_ID, OS_ERR_OBJECT_IN_USE: return-code constants. Required to determine whether return values and subsequent conditional behavior (including undoing changes on failure) are meaningful or redundant.

- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken: returns obj pointer and likely establishes/global-locking context. Critical to know whether it locks the global table, whether it can return NULL, and what lifetime/concurrency guarantees the returned obj has — this affects whether later obj writes/reads are meaningful or race/undefined.

- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: extracts the original ID from the token. Needed to know whether repeated calls produce the same value and whether restoring obj->active_id from it on failure is observable or redundant.

- OS_ObjectIdIsValid: validation predicate used for early return. Its semantics determine if the early-return branch is ever reachable and whether that check is redundant.

- OS_ObjectIdEqual: ID equality predicate. Must know whether it is a pure comparison or has side-effects; it controls the main loop branches and whether assignments/restore code are reachable/necessary.

- OS_WaitForStateChange: called inside the contention loop. Its behavior (blocking, yielding, releasing locks, notifying, or no-op) affects whether the loop is meaningful for synchronization or could be eliminated.

- OS_Unlock_Global: called to unlock the global table. Must know whether it has observable side-effects beyond unlocking (e.g., signaling, resource accounting) and whether calls to it are required for correct behavior or are removable.

These symbols collectively permit determination of (a) which branches and assignments are actually reachable under any valid runtime inputs, (b) which operations have externally observable side-effects (memory changes, synchronization, notifications) and therefore are not dead, and (c) whether some assignments/operations are purely redundant (dead) given the concurrency/locking semantics. Without the above type definitions, constants, and the behavioral contracts of the callees, one cannot reliably decide if any executed operation could be removed without changing program behaviour as required by MISRA C dead-code analysis.
